# Cloud Computing Lab - Program 5
## Program 5: Create Database Using Amazon RDS and Perform CRUD Operations

# Step-by-Step Execution


## Step 1: Verify Existing VPC Resources

First verify the existing VPC resources created in previous programs.

Go to:

AWS Console → VPC Dashboard

Check the following:

VPC: Lab-VPC
CIDR: 10.1.0.0/16

Public Subnet 1: Public-Subnet
CIDR: 10.1.1.0/24

Public Subnet 2: Public-Subnet-2
CIDR: 10.1.2.0/24

Internet Gateway: Lab-IGW

Route Table: Public-RT

The route table should have:

10.1.0.0/16  → local
0.0.0.0/0    → Lab-IGW
Step 2: Enable DNS Resolution and DNS Hostnames in VPC

While creating the RDS database, the following error may appear:

Cannot create a publicly accessible DBInstance.
The specified VPC does not support DNS resolution, DNS hostnames, or both.

To fix this, enable DNS settings for the VPC.

Go to:

VPC Dashboard → Your VPCs

Select:

Lab-VPC

Click:

Actions → Edit VPC settings

Enable:

DNS resolution
DNS hostnames

Click:

Save

This step is important because RDS public access requires DNS resolution and DNS hostnames to be enabled in the selected VPC.

Step 3: Create Security Group for RDS

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Security Groups

Click:

Create security group

Enter the following details:

Security group name: RDS-SG
Description: Allow MySQL access for RDS
VPC: Lab-VPC

Add inbound rule:

Type: MySQL/Aurora
Protocol: TCP
Port: 3306
Source: My IP

If connection fails in the lab network, use:

Source: 0.0.0.0/0

Keep outbound rule as default:

All traffic allowed

Click:

Create security group
Step 4: Create DB Subnet Group

Go to:

RDS Dashboard → Subnet groups

Click:

Create DB subnet group

Enter the following details:

Name: pg05-db-subnet-group
Description: Subnet group for PG05 RDS
VPC: Lab-VPC

Select Availability Zones:

ap-south-1a
ap-south-1b

Select subnets:

Public-Subnet
Public-Subnet-2

Click:

Create

The DB subnet group allows RDS to use the selected subnets inside the VPC.

Step 5: Create RDS MySQL Database

Go to:

RDS Dashboard → Databases

Click:

Create database

Choose:

Database creation method: Standard create
Engine type: MySQL

Template:

Free tier

If free tier is not visible, choose the smallest available instance type.

Step 6: Configure RDS Database Settings

Enter the following database details:

DB instance identifier: pg05-mysql-db
Master username: admin
Master password: Admin12345
Confirm password: Admin12345

In instance configuration, choose:

DB instance class: db.t3.micro / db.t4g.micro / free tier eligible option

In storage settings:

Allocated storage: 20 GB
Storage autoscaling: Disable if visible
Step 7: Configure Connectivity Settings

In the connectivity section, select:

VPC: Lab-VPC
DB subnet group: pg05-db-subnet-group
Public access: Yes
VPC security group: Choose existing
Security group: RDS-SG
Availability Zone: No preference

Database authentication:

Password authentication

Additional configuration:

Initial database name: clouddb

In maintenance settings:

Enable auto minor version upgrade: Enabled

In deletion protection:

Enable deletion protection: Unchecked

Click:

Create database

Wait until the database status becomes:

Available

This may take several minutes.

Step 8: Copy RDS Endpoint

After the database becomes available:

Go to:

RDS → Databases → pg05-mysql-db

Copy the endpoint.

It will look similar to:

pg05-mysql-db.xxxxxxxxxxxx.ap-south-1.rds.amazonaws.com

Also note the port:

3306
Connect to RDS from Ubuntu Terminal
Step 9: Install MySQL Client on Ubuntu

Open Ubuntu terminal and run:

sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install mysql-client -y

Check MySQL client version:

mysql --version
Step 10: Connect to RDS MySQL Database

Use the following command:

mysql -h RDS-ENDPOINT -P 3306 -u admin -p

Example:

mysql -h pg05-mysql-db.xxxxxxxxxxxx.ap-south-1.rds.amazonaws.com -P 3306 -u admin -p

Enter the password:

Admin12345

After successful connection, the MySQL prompt will appear:

mysql>
CRUD Operations

CRUD stands for:

C → Create
R → Read
U → Update
D → Delete
Step 11: Show Existing Databases

Inside the MySQL prompt, run:

SHOW DATABASES;

Expected output:

+--------------------+
| Database           |
+--------------------+
| clouddb            |
| information_schema |
| mysql              |
| performance_schema |
| sys                |
+--------------------+
Step 12: Create Database

Run:

CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS cloud_lab;

Use the database:

USE cloud_lab;

Expected output:

Database changed

This is part of the Create operation.

Step 13: Create Table

Run:

CREATE TABLE students (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(50),
    course VARCHAR(50),
    marks INT
);

Check whether the table is created:

SHOW TABLES;

Expected output:

+---------------------+
| Tables_in_cloud_lab |
+---------------------+
| students            |
+---------------------+

Check table structure:

DESC students;

Expected output:

+--------+-------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+
| Field  | Type        | Null | Key | Default | Extra          |
+--------+-------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+
| id     | int         | NO   | PRI | NULL    | auto_increment |
| name   | varchar(50) | YES  |     | NULL    |                |
| course | varchar(50) | YES  |     | NULL    |                |
| marks  | int         | YES  |     | NULL    |                |
+--------+-------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+

This is also part of the Create operation.

Step 14: Insert Records

Run:

INSERT INTO students (name, course, marks)
VALUES 
('Musaib', 'Cloud Computing', 92),
('Ayaan', 'AWS', 85),
('Sara', 'Database', 88);

Expected output:

Query OK, 3 rows affected

This is the Create operation because records are inserted into the table.

Step 15: Read Records

Run:

SELECT * FROM students;

Expected output:

+----+--------+-----------------+-------+
| id | name   | course          | marks |
+----+--------+-----------------+-------+
|  1 | Musaib | Cloud Computing |    92 |
|  2 | Ayaan  | AWS             |    85 |
|  3 | Sara   | Database        |    88 |
+----+--------+-----------------+-------+

This is the Read operation.

Step 16: Update Record

Update Musaib's marks:

UPDATE students
SET marks = 95
WHERE name = 'Musaib';

Check the updated table:

SELECT * FROM students;

Expected output:

+----+--------+-----------------+-------+
| id | name   | course          | marks |
+----+--------+-----------------+-------+
|  1 | Musaib | Cloud Computing |    95 |
|  2 | Ayaan  | AWS             |    85 |
|  3 | Sara   | Database        |    88 |
+----+--------+-----------------+-------+

This is the Update operation.

Step 17: Delete Record

Delete one record:

DELETE FROM students
WHERE name = 'Ayaan';

Check the final table:

SELECT * FROM students;

Expected output:

+----+--------+-----------------+-------+
| id | name   | course          | marks |
+----+--------+-----------------+-------+
|  1 | Musaib | Cloud Computing |    95 |
|  3 | Sara   | Database        |    88 |
+----+--------+-----------------+-------+

This is the Delete operation.

Step 18: Exit MySQL

Run:

EXIT;

Expected output:

Bye
All SQL Commands Together for Quick Execution

After connecting to MySQL, these commands can be copied and executed together:

SHOW DATABASES;

CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS cloud_lab;

USE cloud_lab;

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS students;

CREATE TABLE students (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(50),
    course VARCHAR(50),
    marks INT
);

SHOW TABLES;

DESC students;

INSERT INTO students (name, course, marks)
VALUES 
('Musaib', 'Cloud Computing', 92),
('Ayaan', 'AWS', 85),
('Sara', 'Database', 88);

SELECT * FROM students;

UPDATE students
SET marks = 95
WHERE name = 'Musaib';

SELECT * FROM students;

DELETE FROM students
WHERE name = 'Ayaan';

SELECT * FROM students;
Expected Final Output

The final output should show successful CRUD operations on the RDS MySQL database.
